<h2 id=3D"4">Modular explicits in pre-OCaml 5.5</h2>
<div class=3D"outline-text-2" id=3D"text-4">
<p>
Archive: <a href=3D"https://inbox.ci.dev/caml-list/6d5f115c-866d-4cc0-a102-=
73657778a0e2@inria.fr/T/">https://inbox.ci.dev/caml-list/6d5f115c-866d-4cc0=
-a102-73657778a0e2@inria.fr/T/</a>
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-org34282a7" class=3D"outline-3">
<h3 id=3D"org34282a7">oleg said</h3>
<div class=3D"outline-text-3" id=3D"text-org34282a7">
<p>
One of the notable features of the just announced OCaml 5.5 are
module-dependent functions, a.k.a. modular explicits. It is a welcome
addition: it lets us express higher-ranked types in the simplest way,
and is particularly good for typed tagless-final code.
</p>

<p>
It should be mentioned however that modular explicits could be done before,
with little or no hassle. Perhaps there is merit to remind of that old
trick~&ndash; especially because it works also with statically unknown modu=
les
(which are out of scope for OCaml 5.5 modular explicits).
</p>

<p>
As the running example we re-use the pretty-printing example in the
OCaml 5.5 announcement (hereafter, Ann55).
</p>

<p>
We start however with a simpler example: pretty-printing a set=20
generated by the <code>Set.Make</code> functor. The example follows the=20
pattern of the pp_map function from Ann55. It is simpler than=20
printing a map because it involves no higher-rank types.
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-ocaml"><code><span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weig=
ht: bold;">let</span> <span style=3D"color: #a7601f;">pp_set</span> (<span =
style=3D"color: #006f00; font-weight: bold;">type</span> <span style=3D"col=
or: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">a</span> <span style=3D"color: #444fcf; fo=
nt-weight: bold;">s</span>)=20
      (<span style=3D"color: #006f00; font-weight: bold;">module</span> <sp=
an style=3D"color: #557400; font-weight: bold;">M</span>: <span style=3D"co=
lor: #557400; font-weight: bold;">Set.S with type elt </span>=3D<span style=
=3D"color: #557400; font-weight: bold;"> a and type t </span>=3D<span style=
=3D"color: #557400; font-weight: bold;"> s</span>)=20
      (<span style=3D"color: #007a9f;">pp_elt</span>:<span style=3D"color: =
#444fcf; font-weight: bold;">Format.formatter-&gt;a-&gt;unit</span>) (<span=
